types of evaporators

  1. unsteady state
  2. ethyl glycol water or other dphe
  3. fins
  4. lumped capacity
  5. radiation
  6. vertical thermosiphon
  7. types of evaporators

based on type mode of HT

  1. non nucleating - falling and climbing film evaporators
  2. nucleating - 1) vapour generation in tubes : vertical thermosiphon long and short 2) vapour generation outside tubes: kettle reboilers, horizontal thermosiphon
  3. flashing
  4. direct contact
    based on fluid circulation
  • natural convection: pool boiling- short tubes
  • natural circulation: thermosiphon and short tubes
  • forced circulation: pumps
  • reboilers

heat sensitive materials

use film evaporators for this.

agitated vessels

type of heat transfer heating cooling
jacket (simple) 400-900 150-600
jacket (glass lining) 200-700 100-350
limpet coil 600-1100 200-700
internal coil 600-1500 250-800

limpet coil assumptions

  1. properties of fluid in the coil don't change
  2. the inlet temperature of fluid in coil is constant
  3. vessel has a flat head
  4. thermal resistance of wall is negligible
  5. batch temperature is constant
  6. heat losses are negligible

ball in water assumptions

  1. conductivity of ball is very very high, so heat loss is by convection only
  2. U is constant with respect to temperature
  3. the temperature throughout the ball is constant
  4. bath temperature is constant

fin assumptions

  1. fin , K, base temperature remain constant. fin material is homogeneous.
  2. bulk temperature of the surrounding remains constant
  3. heat loss across the fin is only by conduction. heat lost to the surrounding is by convection only.
  4. h is constant.
  5. physical properties of fin and surrounding are constant
  6. steady state heat flow
  7. no heat source in the fin
  8. temperature gradient across the film remains constant since width <<< height
  9. joint between the fin and the wall offers negligible resistance.
